, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Old French form of the Late Greek names <i>Eustakhios</i> and <i>Eustathios</i>. These were evidently of separate origin, the former derived from <i>eu</i> ‘well, good’ + <i>stakhys</i> ‘grapes’, the latter from <i>eu</i> + <i>stēnai</i> ‘to stand’. However, the tradition is very confused. The name was introduced in this form to Britain by the Normans, among whom it was popular as a result of the fame of  St Eustace , a Norman nobleman who was said to have been converted to Christianity by the vision of a crucifix between the antlers of the stag he was hunting."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Eustace FitzThomas was born about 1225, in Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Thomas FitzStephan, was 27 and his mother, Mrs Thomas FitzStephan, was 25. He married Johanna la Colvyle about 1245. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died after 1272."},"et":{"Abt 1225–Aft 1272":"umbes 1225–pärast 1272","1225–1272":"1225–1272","1230–1309":"1230–1309","1250–Male":"1250–Surnud","1200–1226":"1200–1226","1202–Female":"1202–Surnud","Aft 1226":"pärast 1226","1226":"1226","1225":"1225","Abt 1245":"umbes 1245","1202":"1202","1200":"1200","Aft 1272":"pärast 1272","1230":"1230","Abt 1225":"umbes 1225","1250":"1250","1272":"1272","1309":"1309","Caswick, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Woolsthorpe, Countylincoln, ENGLAND":"Woolsthorpe, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1225–Aft 1272":"noin 1225–1272 jälkeen","1225–1272":"1225–1272","1230–1309":"1230–1309","1250–Male":"1250–Kuollut","1200–1226":"1200–1226","1202–Female":"1202–Kuollut","Aft 1226":"1226 jälkeen","1226":"1226","1225":"1225","Abt 1245":"noin 1245","1202":"1202","1200":"1200","Aft 1272":"1272 jälkeen","1230":"1230","Abt 1225":"noin 1225","1250":"1250","1272":"1272","1309":"1309","Caswick, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Woolsthorpe, Countylincoln, ENGLAND":"Woolsthorpe, Li